    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-09-14T02:35:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-09-14T02:35:00-05:00" n="284"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d284">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">891.24/253: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Iran</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dreyfus</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tehran</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-09-14T11:00:00+03:25"
                            >September 14, 1942—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 12:39 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>289. Department’s 236, September 9. Prime Minister informs me he has telegraphed
                    Minister, Washington to effect that Iranian Government would prefer a financial
                    adviser even more highly qualified than Dr. Millspaugh. He stated that Iran’s
                    financial problems are vaster and more difficult than 20 years ago and that a
                    man of greatest ability is needed. He alleged that Dr. Millspaugh’s assistants
                    on his last mission here had not been of highest type. I must admit surprise at
                    this about-face on part of Iranian Government concerning Dr. Millspaugh and am
                    at a loss to explain it fully.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Dreyfus</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
